\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Overall Description
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Product Perspective
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The platform aims at replacing the traditional means of communication between taxi drivers and customers, and it is therefore designed as a stand-alone entity that is able to operate with a minimum set of dependencies towards external systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The external interfaces on which the system relies, in order to be operational, are described in the following subsections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Software Interfaces 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Software-Dependencies"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Google Maps API: used in both the back-end and the taxi-side applications, this free API is necessary to elaborate routes and display maps. The system interacts with the API through standard GET requests.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Mnemonic: elaborate routes and display maps 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Source: https://developers.google.com/maps/ 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
GPS: this well known system is required by the mobile applications to get information about the users' position. The interaction happens through the standard GPS protocol provided by the OS of the users' devices.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Mnemonic: get information about the user position 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Source: devices' OSs' protocols 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Red Hat Enterprise Linux: operating system run on the back-end server.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Mnemonics: back-end OS 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Source: https://access.redhat.com/documentation/en/red-hat-enterprise-linux/ 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Apache WebServer: software bundle run on the back-end, which is used to allow interaction between the back-end system and the user-side application. It is used to handle standard HTTP requests from the customer-side web application and to provide CGI services to all the user-side applications.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Mnemonics: web-server 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Source: https://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/ 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
SQLite: DBMS software component run on the back-end, which is used to store user data in a non-resource-intensive fashion.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Mnemonics: DBMS 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Source: https://www.sqlite.org/docs.html 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Device support
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Device support: the back-end system is designed to be run on usual server hardware with a high fault-tolerance degree and supports hardware scaling (such as replication); the mobile applications are designed to be run on ARM based architectures; the user-side web application does not have specific hardware requirements, since it relies on a different level of abstraction (web browser) than its mobile counterpart which is not to be taken into account in the design of the hardware infrastructure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
User interface
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Memory constraints
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is assumed that enough memory will be provided to the system in order to scale in relation to the user traffic. More details on the topic will be provided in the following sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Product functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fully developed platform should implement the following high level functions. 
\end_layout

